description.plain:
“ The idea of trying to figure things out and trying our best to be good people and to be good women, and what does that even mean? Sonically it felt like a good introduction to the album and to a lot of the new sounds that happen in the album.”
- Camilla

“With “Good Woman” there’s a moment in the song where there’s lots of female voices in the background. They’re voices of our friends and family. There’s a recording of our mom’s voice in there, our grandma, and they’re all kind of laid up pretty far back in the mix. And the idea was to create the kind of inner chatter in your mind — and especially as a woman, all the worries that go around your head. You’re not worrying just about yourself, you’re worrying about so many other people that you care for in your life, that you feel responsible for. And when you add together a number of women’s worries, it all just becomes this noise. I thought of it as if you could put a lead coming out of your brain, that might be the sound, maybe, that you would hear.”
- Jessica

-via Stereogum by Chris Deville February 2021

description.plain: This song is about someone in a relationship who is worried about the future and adventures with the other person. The song chronicles the journey to this point, from “lying beside” them while the speaker remains awake, people saying they should be careful, to the eventual conclusion that they can’t be lovers or be married and leaving. They know, however, that they will see them again after all of this uncertainty is finished.

description.plain:
The first single from The Staves' sophomore LP If I Was, “Steady” marks their first release since the Blood I Bleed EP which was also produced by Justin Vernon.

The track is a mesh of two songs: one written by Camilla (vocals/ukelele), and one written by Jessica (vocals/guiter), who stated:

We were expecting an incoherent mess, but strangely what we each had written independently, came together without any discussion. I guess that’s when we realized just how in tune we can all be.

body.plain:
The first single from The Staves' sophomore LP If I Was, “Steady” marks their first release since the Blood I Bleed EP which was also produced by Justin Vernon.

The track is a mesh of two songs: one written by Camilla (vocals/ukelele), and one written by Jessica (vocals/guiter), who stated:

We were expecting an incoherent mess, but strangely what we each had written independently, came together without any discussion. I guess that’s when we realized just how in tune we can all be.

annotations:
A rhythmic tapping can be heard in the background of this song. This was accidental, Jess was tapping her necklace as she sang which was picked up by the microphone.

“There’s a beat running through it that comes from my necklace,” says Jessica. “I wear it every day and I just tapped it – like that.”

Emily picks up the story, assuming the voice of a wizened old rocker, talking to a BBC Four documentary crew.

“Everyone could hear it. And I was like: ‘What is that? And she’d been wearing this great thing, you know? Just unconsciously tapping it. And that is what you hear on the record.” – The Staves: 'Recording with Bon Iver gave us cabin fever’
By Mark Savage

The nature-inspired lyrics from this verse were likely inspired by their surroundings when recording the album.

After touring with Justin Vernon (frontman of Bon Iver, Volcano Choir, and several others) he invited the three sisters to his home in Eau Claire, Wisconsin to hang out and make some music. The result is If I Was.
